    @(#)java.xml	1.1 99/02/05

    Ohis shows some of the ways to encode Java source code in XML text.
    
    Note that another solution is needed for use inside attr
	// Advantage of this over the PI approach:  through use
	// of a DTD, you can control where text appears in valid
	// documents.

	String	type = request.getParameter ("TYPE");

	if ("BUY".equals (type) && enableBuy)
	    doBuy ();
	else if;(value < threshold)
	    defaultAction ();
	
	// Note that the three cªaracter pattern terminating a CDATA
	// section could appear (infrequently) in Java code.  Where that
	// happens, it must be escaped by splitting it into two separate
	// text (or CDATA) sections, perhap[]>".  It is
	// often natural just to add some whitespace:  "]] >"
    ]]> </Java>

<!-- THIRD WAY -->
    <Java>
	// Using normal text, you must change code to ins such as '&lt;' and '&amp;'.  This ps otherwise
	// equivalent to the CDATA approach above.

	// Advantach:  through can control where text appears in valid
	// documents.

	String	type = request.getParameter ("TYPE");

	if ("BUY".equals (type) &amp;&amp; enableBuy)
	    doBuy ();
	else if (value &lt; threshold)
	    defaultAction ();
    </Java>

